note.p: For samples of Forman’s hand, see the entries in his casebooks in which he is listed as a practitioner.
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Simon Forman’.

Most of the content of the casebooks is written in Napier’s hand; for examples see most of the entries in which he is listed as practitioner; for a full alphabet and set of symbols in Napier’s hand see our handwriting guide.
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Richard Napier’.
This scribe was the copyist in whose hand we have Forman’s 1603 entries; we have to date seen no evidence of his involvement in the Napier volumes.
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Unidentified Hand (1603)’.

This hand first appeared in one rogue entry, presumably from Napier’s practice, copied into a volume of Forman’s (as CASE5292). It has now appeared on f. 6v of MS Ashmole 406, volume 46 of Napier’s casebooks, in May 1629, and on p. 70 of MS Ashmole 194, volume 47, in January 1630. One distinctive feature to look out for is this scribe’s tendency to use a &crossedp; () when writing p m (as in ‘ me’’); another is that the charts, drawn freehand, end up with very curvy diamond shapes in the middle, unlike the rather straighter figures achieved by Napier and his other assistants.
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Unidentified Hand (1629 on)’.

This is Napier’s curate (sometimes referred to as ‘Mr Gerenc(e)’). His hand is superficially similar to Napier’s, but fussier; he records times in the style ‘ho. 1. 45. a m.’; cf. Forman’s ‘45 p 1 an’ m’’ and Napier’s ‘hor. 1. 45. ant m’. Unlike Napier, he can spell ‘Alice’, but not ‘Elisabeth’, from which he habitually omits the ‘i’. For examples of his hand, see the entries in which he is listed as a practitioner; for a full alphabet and set of symbols in James’s hand see our handwriting guide.

In a few entries James has added a planetary symbol at the end of the question paragraph representing the Lord of the Hour; if this is encountered, the planet should be encoded using &MarsLord;, &JupiterLord; et al. The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Gerence James’.

Sir Richard Napier’s hand begins to appear in the casebooks from 1629. For an example of his looser hand see the second volume of his own casebooks, MS Ashmole 340, from f. 111r on; for an example of his neater hand see Ashmole 232, p. 12. His hand can be difficult to distinguish from Unidentified (1624–1634) below — unknown-f — but several features should usually make it possible to tell Sir Richard’s apart. (See the top half of MS Ashmole 232, p. 17, for the two hands side by side.: unknown-f is in the top left of the page; Richard Napier the nephew has written the entry in the top right, and large parts of the other two entries on the page.) The young Richard Napier often uses a slightly sickle-shaped (that is, secretary-shaped) ‘h’ that drops below the line, as well as occasional italic ‘h’s that do not drop below the line; he uses an italic ‘e’ most often, with occasional additions of a secretary (theta-shaped) e or an epsilon-shaped e; his ampersands tend to include a stroke that curves anticlockwise round the character to the very top or past it. His capital D typically has an elaborate C-shaped curve at the back of it. When he writes times in the morning he usually writes ‘a. m.’ (or in one instance ‘an. m.’), but not ‘ant m’. Like other scribes from Napier’s casebooks, he often uses ℞ to indicate a treatment (something to be taken by the patient) rather than a recipe.
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Richard Napier (the nephew)’.

A practitioner who stands in for Napier during some periods of Napier’s absence. His very distinctive hand appears first in August 1605, then for extended periods during the springs of 1607 and 1608 and the summers of 1612 and 1614. His latest appearance to date is in July 1618. His hand was previously known as unknown-b, ‘Unidentified (1605–1618), so for examples of this hand see the entries on the site in which ‘Unidentified (1605–1618) is currently listed as a practitioner. In cases in which Napier is away Willoughby has a habit, particularly in his earlier entries, of referring to Napier in either the second or the third person, usually with notes to the effect that the querent will visit or write personally to Napier after his return.

He consistently writes e.g. ‘y. 30’ rather than ‘30 y’ and capitalises ‘A. M.’ (or ‘Ant. M.’) and ‘P. M.’ (or ‘Post M.’). He writes his Moon symbols with the convex side facing East, i.e. back-to-front as compared to Napier’s and James’s form. Like Napier, he habitually omits the ‘i’ from ‘Alice’. He is inordinately fond of full stops, which in his entries sometimes occur after (and occasionally also before) every single word, numeral or symbol in the question section. When he really does mean something roughly equating to a modern full stop, he generally uses a punctuation mark consisting of three dots forming a (more or less) equilateral triangle (⸫), which should be encoded as &threeDotStop;. He normally prefaces any treatment notes with ℞, which means that this can not in his entries be taken as a a reliable indicator of a recipe (or of angelic advice from Raphael).
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Mr Willoughby’.
The hand used in CASE24616 and CASE24617. Presumably an assistant of Napier’s, but this is not Gerence James’s hand.
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Unidentified Hand (1610)’.

An associate of Napier’s who on two occasions stood in for Napier in his practice. The first of his two appearances was in May 1611; his second was in July 1612. It is possible that this is Napier’s curate from 1610 to 1612, Thomas Stokes, but other than the timing there is no evidence of that. One notable characteristic of this scribe is a tendency to give ages in Latin (‘ætat. 50’) in passages otherwise entirely in English. For examples of this hand see the cases in which he is listed as a practitioner.
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Unidentified Hand (1611–1612)’.

A hand that first appears on 25 June 1622, providing a few notes and calculations for a nativity in Ashmole 223, f. 168v, and last appears on 3 March 1624 (Ashmole 413, f. 95r). For an example of this hand see also Ashmole 413, f. 82v and Ashmole 413. f. 83r (images aca0188 and aca0189). This is probably identical to Unidentified Hand B in Ashmole 363: note the distinctive ampersands. Like Unidentified (1605–1618) above, this scribe uses ‘℞’ more freely than Napier and it is not always safe to take it as indicating a recipe. Another feature worth looking out for is the use of ‘æ’ for ‘ætate’, before an age. The date range for this hand suggests that it may be John Miles, Napier’s curate from before March 1622 to September 1624.
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Unidentified Hand (1622–1624)’.

The rector of Thornton in Buckinghamshire from at least 1616 until at least 1636, Bredon corresponded with Napier on astrological matters, consulted him at least twice (in 1617 and 1618), and supplied Napier several times with natal charts at Napier’s request during the later 1620s. The figure and the text below it on Ashmole 405, f. 331Ar are in Bredon’s impressively neat italic hand. For examples of his typical hand see various letters to Napier in Ashmole 240, ff. 87r (biy0183), 91r (biy0191), 92r (biy0193), 93r (biy0195); for examples of astrological figures drawn by him see Ashmole 240, f. 78r (biy0165), f. 79r (biy0167) and f. 86r (biy0181), each of which also has associated notes in his italic hand; for a more extensive example of his italic hand see Ashmole 240, f. 85r (biy0179).
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘William Bredon’.

Napier’s curate 1612–16 and after that an occasional visitor to Great Linford; his hand appears intermittently in the casebooks from at least 1615 on. Charts produced by Wallis are typically drawn differently from Napier’s: where in Napier’s charts the diagonal lines drawn from corner to corner meet in a cross (×) at the centre, in Wallis’s charts a blank square is normally drawn at the centre. See for example CASE42728. Wallis sometimes writes calculations for his charts so that the ‘sidereal noon’ is the second item listed, rather than the first (as almost all the other practitioners and scribes do). His Saturn symbols are curious and angular (there is an example at the last link) and very distinctive. For examples of his hand see the entries in which he is listed as a practitioner.
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Robert Wallis’.

A hand that first appears on 21 December 1624 (see f. 129r of Ashmole 402), but whose entries otherwise appear ca. 1629–1634 (see e.g. p. 323 of Ashmole 214, or f. 15r of Ashmole 412). The dates of his association with Napier match those of Ralph Ruddle, Napier’s curate from some time around late 1624 or early 1625, and it may be noteworthy that several entries in later volumes for people called Ruddle and/or from Ralph Ruddle’s home county of Wiltshire are written in this hand. We currently lack convincing evidence that this hand is Ruddle’s, however.

The hand is similar to the neater form of Sir Richard Napier’s, but less rounded, and there are differences that should usually make it possible to tell them apart: this scribe writes ‘L’s whose ascenders are kinked; he always, or almost always, uses epsilon-shaped ‘e’s; his ‘h’s are italic and do not drop below the line (unlike Sir Richard’s). When giving times in the morning he sometimes writes ‘a. m.’ and sometimes ‘ant. m.’. When he writes ‘p m’, usually (though not quite always) the loop on the ‘p’ is not quite closed, and ends with a short but noticeable horizontal stroke (as in p. 14 of Ashmole 232, in the top left corner or f. 70r of Ashmole 238, top left and top right). His Cancer symbols (♋) are typically horizontal, like two tadpoles swimming past each other, whereas both Napiers write their Cancer symbols like the number 69. For a useful side-by-side view of unknown-f and Richard Napier the younger, see the top half of MS Ashmole 232, p. 17. unknown-f is in the top left of the page; Richard Napier the nephew has written the entry in the top right, and large parts of the other two entries on the page.
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Unidentified Hand (1624–1634)’.

Napier’s assistant towards the end of Napier’s life. Assuming that Black’s identification of his hand is correct, samples can be seen in Ashmole 412 at the bottom of f. 246r and in neat form on f. 322r; and judging from the overlined ‘Mr’ with the 2-shaped r, as well as the general shape of the writing, it also appears in the question sections of three entries on f. 16v and one on f. 17r. He also has a less neat hand that appears in several entries and notes; this is visible, below his neater hand, on p. 229 of Ashmole 416. A few of his notable habits are: in dates he tends to use numeral abbreviations for his months, such as ‘9bris’ for ‘Novembris’ and ‘xbris’ for ‘Decembris’. When he writes ‘p M’ or ‘p Mer’, he typically uses a lower-case ‘p’ and an upper-case ‘M’. When writing Latin he marks instances of the letter ‘u’ with an accent to distinguish them from the letter ‘n’ (though they are distinguishable on the basis of shape anyway). His Scorpio symbol (♏) is very different from the other scribes’, with the tail of the scorpion resembling a curl rather than an arrow.
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Theodoricus Gravius’.

A hand that appears in November 1628 in Ashmole 405 on f. 330v. It looks somewhat similar to Robert Wallis’s hand, and like Wallis, this scribe (in the available sample) writes his days with a ‘d’ for ‘die’, as in ‘d. ☿’. Unlike most of Wallis’s, his charts do not have a square in the centre of them (instead they resemble Forman’s and Napier’s). The Saturn symbols in this hand (see for instance the entry in the top left corner of the page at the last link) are far more normal-looking than Wallis’s.
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Unidentified Hand G’.

A hand that first appears in December 1628 in Ashmole 407 on f. 11v, copying judgment given by William Bredon, then again in February 1630 in Ashmole 194 on p. 106 writing a question out, and in March 1630 in Ashmole 194 on p. 164, writing the whole of an entry. This scribe/assistant may turn out to be the same as unknown-x, the person who copied out Forman’s 1603 entries, though unknown-x seems to use an italic ‘h’ at the beginnings of words more often than this scribe does.
The content of handNote for this hand should be ‘Unidentified Hand H’.
